{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-js","path":"/posts/peacock","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"id":"df9713d9-5def-55d6-b806-93e131962f57","html":"<p><code class=\"language-text\">Peacock</code> is a simple extension that lets you identify individual projects when working on multiple of them at once. </p>\n<p>Just head to <a href=\"https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=johnpapa.vscode-peacock\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">VS Code Marketplace</a> and install the extension.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 960px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/914c7/peacock.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.916666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/8ac56/peacock.webp 240w,\n/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/d3be9/peacock.webp 480w,\n/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/e46b2/peacock.webp 960w,\n/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/0e613/peacock.webp 978w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 960px) 100vw, 960px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/8ff5a/peacock.png 240w,\n/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/e85cb/peacock.png 480w,\n/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/d9199/peacock.png 960w,\n/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/914c7/peacock.png 978w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 960px) 100vw, 960px\"\n          type=\"image/png\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          src=\"/static/cb421210a7cc14901b801094e39b5210/d9199/peacock.png\"\n          alt=\"Screenshot\"\n          title=\"Screenshot\"\n          loading=\"lazy\"\n          style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>This extension colorizes the workspace(border) with a unique color to pinpoint the exact project you want to switch to when working on multiple VS code workspace. As described by the project, ‚ÄúSubtly change the color of your Visual Studio Code workspace. Ideal when you have multiple VS Code instances, use VS Live Share, or use VS Code‚Äôs Remote features, and you want to quickly identify your editor.‚Äù</p>\n<p>After installation just switch to the workspace and use command palette options, ‚ÄúSurprise Me with Random color‚Äù or ‚ÄúChange to a favorite color‚Äù to give amazing color to current project. It saves your color preference in <code class=\"language-text\">.vscode</code> folder settings of the workspace, so that the same color comes into effect when you reopen the same workspace. </p>\n<p>Refer its documentation <a href=\"https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=johnpapa.vscode-peacock\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">here</a></p>\n<p>These colors work great with the default VSCode theme and seamlessly blend in the default VSCode.</p>\n<p>Official Repo: <a href=\"https://github.com/johnpapa/vscode-peacock\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Peacock</a> by John Papa</p>\n<hr>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/peacock","tagSlugs":null},"frontmatter":{"date":"2020-01-17T18:05:00.738Z","description":"Change color of your VS Code workspace to manage multiple project at once","tags":null,"title":"Identify workspace when working with multiple projects ü¶ö","socialImage":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/posts/peacock"}}}